{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9ae3edaa-7e82-4646-a8fd-6040f77bde27","content":"This is a TUnit project using Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). TUnit uses `--treenode-filter` for filtering. The command is:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nThe treenode filter path follows `/<Assembly>/<Namespace>/<Class>/<Test>`, where `*` is a wildcard. This matches all tests inside the `SmsNotificationTests` class regardless of assembly, namespace, or test name.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b6c0e3e3-81bc-4bc2-8030-95a6aa8d4586","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project (v0.6.120). TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. For MTP-based runners, filtering by class uses the `--treenode-filter` option with the syntax:\n\n```\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nWait, let me think about TUnit's filter syntax. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform. The filter syntax for MTP with TUnit uses `--treenode-filter`.\n\nThe treenode filter path for TUnit is typically: `/<assembly>/<namespace>/<class>/<test>`\n\n\nThe treenode filter format follows the pattern `/<Assembly>/<Namespace>/<Class>/<Test>`, so to match just the class `SmsNotificationTests`, I'd use `--treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"` to capture all tests within that class. I could also try a property-based filter approach targeting the namespace directly.\n\nSince TUnit is built on Microsoft.Testing.Platform natively, I can run it either as an executable with `dotnet run` or use `dotnet test` with the treenode filter, though I need to verify which approach works best given that TUnit projects typically have `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>`.","outputTokens":649,"requestId":"67C7:14F926:2BB1889:30521C5:69FD3E81"},"id":"eefb02e1-cdea-4c2e-b6be-11aeafeac2a1","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:38:23.805Z","parentId":"cacd8795-63b5-4bff-9bcc-3f8773d99e06"}
